review_blob: The nose immediately gives away the style, as you can smell the tartness. This one is pretty intensely sour, dry, and easy drinking. I should have brought back a few of these from my trip to Bend.
Pours opaque black/dark brown. Sourness immediately on the nose, which dominates the taste. Some subtle berry notes as well. Overall, a very solid sour ale.
Lots of white wine on the nose and on the finish. In between, flavors from the rye and the Brett meld together very well - almost indistinguishable from each other.

On draft in Nashville. Very little aroma, and probably in keeping with the style...  Very little of any particular taste. On the plus side, theres nothing to complain about. A very simple beer thats perfect if you desire something lightly hopped that goes down easy.

Out of the bottle: very well carbonated. Lots of Belgian yeasty notes on the nose. However, these dont carry over to the taste, and I get a lot of roasty flavors - and maybe some root beer - that I dont usually taste in a dubbel.
Pours a fluffy white head, slightly hazy. Some funkiness and a bit of citrus on the nose. Very mild malt flavor with a bit of hop flavor. Very dry finish.
beer_name: Jester King Noble King Hoppy Farmhouse Ale (Batch 1-10)

review_blob: Overall, a fairly solid quad. Some caramel and raisin on the nose that translates initially to the taste, followed by some flavors that probably come from the candi sugar, then a little bit of heat from the alcohol and a dry finish.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Fantastic example of a Saison, a must try. Definitely Brett on the nose immediately. Lots of Belgian yeasty flavors with some lemony citrus. Dry and with very little malt overall.
A little piney on the nose. Definitely a solid balance between hop bitterness and hop sweetness.
A solid IPA with a mild finish that keeps you coming back for more. Cant tell if theres some Summit or Citra in there.. A little oniony and garlicy from the hops.

You can definitely tell youll be drinking an imperial as soon as you open the can. I second the reviewer below that it is syrupy and the hop flavor is kind of muddled with the malt background. Still a solid beer worth a try, though.
Lots of the Galaxy immediately hits the nose. I also get a lot of hop sweetness that I really enjoy, followed by a good balance of bitterness.

120 minute barleywine? Perhaps that name would be more appropriate. If you want a drink that sits somewhere between a beer and a glass of whiskey, this may be for you. Im not going to go into the details, as I think everyone will get something different out of it, depending on your palate and the age of the beer. Enjoy.
Funk immediately on the nose. One person described a mustardy tartness, and Id have to agree. Some nice sour notes on a dry finish.
A solid, well-rounded IPA. It starts with a nice citrus aroma, continues with a little bit of malt flavor, and finishes with a light hop sweetness of grapefruit.
beer_name: Cigar City Jai Alai India Pale Ale

review_blob: Pours a very dark brown, beige head. The aroma is very fruit. Taste is a balance of fruity esters with caramel and a very dry finish. I could drink a lot of these.
On tap in 12 South. A well balanced milk stout. The sweetness is more subdued than most other milk stouts. It has a nice chocolate finish. Very good overall.
beer_name: Straight To Ale Lily Flagg Milk Stout

review_blob: Pours amber with a fluffy, white-ish head. Very well balanced between those Belgian yeasty flavors, some additional fruitiness, and a little bitterness. My only complaint is that it tastes just a bit on the sweet side.
I really dont find anything enjoyable about this beer at all. Theres some strange (albeit subtle) metallic aftertaste thats always present, and I always feel dirty when I drink one.
To be fair, I drank this after a dry stout, so its kind if hard to rate. Pretty refreshing, a golf course in the middle of summer would be a perfect venue.
Lets see. Its dark, its roasty, its very, very dry. Overall, a great example of a dry stout.
Exactly what I want in this style. The hoppiness balances really well with the Belgian yeasty flavors.
beer_name: Green Flash / Founders Linchpin White India Pale Ale

review_blob: Pours opaque. Aroma isnt very strong, a little sweet with some caramel. Taste is mostly dark chocolate. Theres nothing overwhelming about this one, just very well-rounded.

16.9 ounce bottle, about a month and a half old. Brought back from Boulder thanks to beerproject. I think everything that could be said about this beer had been said... its just so well balanced for a double.

Batch 22: Pours a hazy amber with a thin, white head. Theres very little of the sour flavor on the nose. The sourness and acidity balance nicely with the rest if the beer. I bought this one just in time. Someone grabbed every one left on the shelf not 5 seconds after I picked up mine.
Comfortably toasty. Nothing overpowering about this one, just a solid porter. Goes great with a little dark chocolate as an after dinner beer.
